<br>
You've seen them before; you know what they are.  They are the backbone of a successful raid - the Raid Channel.<br>
<br>
The Raid Channel is there to get information quickly where it needs to go.  Usually, it is instructions from the raid leader(s).  A lot of the time it is the MA telling the other melees when to attack.  Other times, it is the Crowd Control team telling the rabid melees who to stop attacking while they mez them ( if you're assisting correctly, you don't really need to pay attention to these ).<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, the Raid Channel is also where people ask redundant questions.  Repetatively.  Over and over.  Ad Naseum.  It's also where people debate things.  Idle chatter also seeps into the Raid Channel.  These things do not belong in the raid channel.  They belong in the &quot;kcog&quot; channel.  Well, except the griping, finger pointing, etc.  That doesn't belong anywhere during the raid.<br>
<br>
Group leaders.  group Leaders.  group LEADERS.  Notice the second word -&gt; Leaders.  These are the people who the Raid Leader trusts, the people that have BeenThereDoneThat(tm), and the people that know the answers to almost all of your questions.  If you have a question, ask it in your group.  There's a very good chance you will get your answer that way.  If your group doesn't know the answer, guess what?  It's the group leader's responsibility to get the answer for you.  They know how to get your answer the correct way.  Trust them.<br>
<br>
Example:<br>
&quot;Who is the MA?&quot;  This question should NEVER be heard in the Raid Channel.  One of the following things are going on:<br>
<br>
1) The Raid Leader hasn't selected one yet, so you CAN'T know<br>
2) The Raid Leader has announced one, and you missed it<br>
3) The Raid Leader has forgotten to announce it<br>
<br>
If it's (1), then the question is moot.  If it's (2), then your Group Leader or other group members will answer it for you.  If it's (3), your group leader will remind the Raid Leader to select one after you ask the question in group.<br>
<br>
I'm going to go out on a limb and guess that most of the people that read these boards already know and typically abide by these things.  The biggest problem is random_warrior_01 or guild_cleric_03 that gets casually invited to the raid who doesn't know these things.  Guess what?  It's YOUR job to let them know these things if you invite them to the raid.  They won't know, otherwise, and do the most basic things wrong because you didn't school them on raid ettiquette / procedure / strategy.  There are writeups on these boards on each of the big raids I have attended.  If you are going, you need to read them and pass that info on to the people you invite.  Post a link to them in your guild's forums.<br>
<br>
The /assist [ma] thing has been beaten into the ground.  Unfortunately, for good reason.  We're dealing with characters whose average level exceeds 50 on these raids, typically.  There are still people who don't know how to assist.  It's mind-boggling to some, but it's true and has to be accepted as a fact.  Here's a way to make sure that everyone knows how to do it:<br>
<br>
If you are a group leader ( a position of leadership and knowledge bestowal ), after your group is announced, get your members in your group ASAP.  Have all your members make their assist keys right then, except substitute YOU ( the group leader ) for the MA in the hotkey.  Then, pick random targets and ask your group members individually to assist you and then tell you what you are targeting.  After you are confident their assist key works, have them change it to the MA ( if announced ).  If the MA isn't announced, as soon as they are, have them change it to the MA.  Then, have them test it ( send a tell to the MA to target something if you need to ).  Some of the names I see on the raids are not the easiest things to spell.  Test your assist key.  Test your secondary assist key the same way.  If every group leader forces their gorup to test their assist key, then at least everyone on the raid will have an assist key.  The only thing left is getting them to use it.<br>
<br>
Except for a few choice people ( like the crowd control team, MA, etc ), you should never use anything but your assist key to target the mob you are going to kill.  When do you hit it?  AFTER the MA calls for everyone to attack.  Don't hit it when the pull comes in.  Don't hit is right after random_mob_01 dies.  If the MA hasn't called for everyone to assist, then they still have the right to change targets.  If you are using F8, or your mouse, or any other way to target the mob you are going to attack, you are DOING IT WRONG.  You are JEAPORDIZING THE RAID.  That's not why you are there, and you don't want to be wrong or jeapordize the raid.  You want a successful raid, right?  Don't be a goat, Charlie Brown.<br>
<br>
On a raid like Hate, there will be unmezzable ( or mostly unmezzable ) mobs.  If one of these adds, the MA will switch to it.  There will usually be a call to switch targets.  If there isn't a call, it's up to you to know what mobs can't be mezzed so keep a lookout for any of these adding.  When they switch to it, your job is to:<br>
<br>
1) Turn off Autoattack<br>
2) Wait until the MA calls for the assist<br>
3) Hit your assist key<br>
4) Attack the mob<br>
<br>
If you don't wait for the MA to call for the assist, you have a chance of getting aggro.  What does that mean?  It means that mana is going to be wasted healing you.  When mana is wasted, that's that much less mana available when that &quot;OH HOLY CRAP!&quot; pull comes in.  It means you are not doing your job.  There's nothing special about getting aggro - anyone can do it.  It's nothing to be proud of, and possibly something to be ashamed of.<br>
<br>
There are times that you will get aggro from a multi-pull because the mob that hasn't been attacked runs into the camp and you are the closest Lunch-in-a-Shell the mob sees.  You will get attacked.  What do you do?  Well, you sure don't attack it back.  You let your healer heal you, you let your CC Team control the mob, and you wait for the MA to call for the assist, at which time you hit your assist key and start wailing away with the rest of the melees.  If the mob that is on you isn't controlled when the assist is called, and you know it backstabs, you may want to not turn your back to it.<br>
<br>
KCoG raids get more and more impressive as they go.  The way to keep raising the bar is to keep them organized.  The path to organization is knowledge.  When you have a raid of knowledgable, organized people, you have a POWERFUL force.  You have a force that will soon be able to join the channel &quot;kcogvs&quot; and =know= that the night is going to end well. <p>Zymyool, Officer of the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Ancient Adventurers</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  on the Karana Server<br>
