<br>
As an extention to what Qamgine brings up, its important to simply ride that assist key and not to do anything till you get the mob.<br>
<br>
Watch for commands.  I always use a seperate chat channel for raid commands so there's no excuse for not seeing them.  Change that chat channel to bright red if you must or pink or purple or whatever.  But I usually have a chat channel dedicated to commands.<br>
<br>
So that when an MA calls for a switch the result is immediate.  Its also why I try to put the MA along with the enchatner, so they can communicate within the group.<br>
<br>
If the lag is bad for you (as it is for most on these 70+ person raids) ride that assist key.  Keep hitting it till you get something.  Then check its health bar.  If its full do NOT attack till you start seeing it go down.<br>
<br>
Also dont attack till you see the MA call for the assists.  Never, ever, ever attack till then.  If the MA doesnt call it, you dont attack.  Ever.  If the MA dies because he forgot and ended up tanking the Dracoliche alone, then so be it.  The SA probably wont make the same mistake.<br>
<br>
Once the MA calls for the assist, double check what you see in your target box against what mob the MA called.  Lag as well as the MA having to cycle through mobs depending on what the enchanter tells him, can cause /assist to lie to you at first.  Try smacking it a few times even after you get the target up to make sure, and make sure the health on the target is dropping before engaging.<br>
<br>
Especially if you are using /raid there is no reason not to wait.  There's no xp to KS and no loot to ninja.  You get no points or bragging rights for getting the kill shot or most damage.  Especially if you have 70 people, the mob is going down.  And it will go down a lot faster if you are positive you are on the right target than if you screw up and break a mez or start too early and gain aggro and need heals which also cost mana that could have been used in a nuke.  Judgement and Wildfire do good damage.<br>
<br>
Personally I find it easier to simply make groups rather than let group leaders do it themselves.  I inevitably find the clerics distributed incorrectly and end up having to remake things anyway.  But then again, I have a fair bit of experience in making groups and it generally takes me less time to actually make them than to wait for people to make their own and then contact me with who is in them.<br>
<br>
It also allows for customization for efficency.<br>
<br>
Example, for me only the first 4 groups matter.  All the others consist of 1 tank, 1 healer (preferably a druid so they can port if necessary) and everyone else ad hoc and usually by level.  So group 14 tends to be the lowest levels and are often just a makeshift group till openings happen elsewhere.<br>
<br>
Within the first 4 groups, the first one is what I call my Command Group.  This consists of a tank as group leader (usually a decent ranger or paladin) and the puller as well as a cleric if possible and another druid if not.  The other 2 slots (since I place myself in this group as well) are random people.<br>
<br>
This allows for close communication between myself and the puller.  We need to be on the same page as the Raid Leader generally has a better idea of the status of the raid than the puller.  Or should.<br>
<br>
The second group is my Main Assist group which consists of the MA, and best cleric in the raid, and the enchanter.  I usually put a second cleric (usually possible only on Hate raids) or a druid.  The rest of it consists of at least 1 other tank (preferably a paladin for additional spot heals) and the SECONDARY shaman if I'm blesssed to have more than 1.  If there is no druid the last slot is always a wizard for evacs.  If I am blessed to have a bard he always takes the place of the second tank in this group.  Also, a high level necro goes here in place of the wizard if I have both one and a druid to secondary heal.<br>
<br>
The third group is my SA group.  Please note, its an odd number, this is important for later.  It consists of the SA, my second best cleric, and my main shaman.  Assuming I even have one.  I also try to keep a second cleric or druid here.  The other slots are random except again I have a wizard here if no druid for evacs.<br>
<br>
The 4th group consists of my 4th best tank and a 3rd cleric if possible.  Otherwise a druid/shaman or druid/druid combo will suffice.  The rest of the slots are random.  <br>
<br>
Note, while ideally I'd have at least 4 clerics so I can slip one in each of the 4 main groups, only the second and third groups really need them.  And even the third doesnt necessarily need them if your good.<br>
<br>
Also note, you only evac in Fear for breaks if something goes wrong.  Once the break is accomplished you can redistribute the wizards wherever.<br>
<br>
The rest of the groups are pretty much random.  Except that I try to put my 3th best tank in group 5.  And I try to keep a healer of some sort in each of them.<br>
<br>
The reason my 3rd best tank doesnt go into group 4 is double.<br>
<br>
First off, I usually only break Fear and Hate with a max of 4 groups.  This gives me an experienced and good tank who remains safe and intact to lead a second wave if necessary.<br>
<br>
Also, sometimes it becomes necessary on trains to have both the MA and SA choose and fight different targets.  When this happens I have even groups assist the MA (since he is group 2 they assist themselves) and odd groups assisting the SA.  Thus group 4 with the 4th best tank will assist the MA whereas the 5th group with the 3rd best tank will assist the MA.  This gives a good balance of tankage in case the MA or SA goes down.<br>
<br>
The ability to customize based upon experiance to me outweights the hassles of actually having to make groups.  Note, this remains a good tactic for alliances and guilds that work well together and communicate well.  But I find KCoG is simply to random for this to work out well.<br>
<br>
Often my MA is based upon ability and my confidence on them rather than level and class.  I've related a level 60 warrior with his epics to leading group 4 and had a level 60 Ranger as MA.  Dont attempt this tactic against VS though. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The second and third groups are fairly complex to make and actual makeup does sort of depend on who is there.  But its vital that some classes like bards and necro's end up in the groups that will make the most use of them for mana and hps regen.<br>
<br>
Now you could make the argument that with 70+ people it doesnt really make a difference.  And thats true.<br>
<br>
But doing it yourself and putting things together carefullly can be the difference between doing the plane in 4 hours and walking out and taking 8 hours and porting out.<br>
<br>
Now I grant you that each raid leader does things their own way and its important that they do what works for them as opposed to what someone else tells them is the &quot;right&quot; way.  But I havent seen much in the way of taling about group makeup and I've found that to be one of the most important duties of a Raid Leader.  However you do it, how your groups are made up and how they function togehter is generally the difference between taking the 4 hours or 8.<br>
<br>
The one thing I have to emphasize is that the Raid Leader must lead.  They cannot be doing anything else.  They cannot be a healer or mez'er or main tank.  They must stand back and simply watch and keep an eye on things.  Its hard to juggle groups, mana status, hit point status, mob status, as well as tells and commands, if you are also fighting.<br>
<br>
It is so easy to lose track of things when you are fighting that you miss an add that takes down a cleric or enchanter and by the time the group reports this its too late and your facing a wipeout when you could have orded a target switch or evac if necessary and saved most people.<br>
<br>
Believe me, this is one of the hardest things any Raid Leader can do.  I think to a large extent all of us who do this are control freaks.  But especially on plane raids there's simply too much going on.  You need to step back and be a General instead of a captain or colonel.  It sort of sucks to stand back while others are killing and doing &quot;important&quot; stuff.  But you do owe it to the raid and their time and xp to be above that and actually lead.<br>
<br>
With raids lasting 4-8 hours of constant combat, you need to stay as fresh and undistracted as possible.<br>
<br>
Also for us caster raid leaders, casting means using mana which means sitting which means increased aggro which means the potential for a mob homing in on you and killing you.  And a dead Raid leader can all to easily mean a dead raid.<br>
<br>
Raid discipline isnt just making sure people are doing their jobs and assisting.  It also means making sure your raid leader is doing their job and enforcing the raid rules and keeping an eye on everything.<br>
<br>
Things are a bit easier today with increased armor and equipment.  But even so, the difference between a salvagable situation and a camp out or evac situation is often measured in seconds.  And its up to the raid leader to identify and make use of those seconds.  Even with DA there must remain sufficent tanks available to keep the mobs off the camping clerics, which is sometimes harder than it sounds.  And you've got seconds to decide if you should camp the cleric because your screwed (what do you mean Inny came with the Deathrot Knight!?) and whether you can make it if barely if you hang onto the cleric (Cool, Inny was just a ghost...too bad the Maestro wasnt).<br>
<br>
With all the things to keep in mind, its amazing how anyone has any fun at all.  But I've found that obeying the rules and working together often results in MORE fun than just doing your own thing.  Success has a sweet scent all its own. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
PS.  I'm not saying any KCoG raid leader doesnt lead.  Just that a) I've seen many that take on too many things or are watching the wrong things and b) its a good thing to keep in mind.  I've been warned by my own guild leader with guild suspension for not following my own advice on more than 1 occasion.<br>
<br>
Although its funniest when you get warned and then the next week your guild leader does the exact same thing.  I really live for moments like that.  I swear, I can see &quot;Doh!&quot; pop on top of his head...<br>
