<br>
A note on sending tells. Don't! Yes, he knows you are there. How you ask? Well did you turn anon and role off? Did you turn LFG on? That's how the RL makes groups.<br>
<br>
Also, just to tie in a few points. There is usually a designated spammer. They are usually spamming the same thing over and over. In both channels. (When I spam I throw a /ooc to tell people to join the raid channel.) If you don't know what you are supposed to do (it's okay not to know) send them a tell. They are more than happy to help. Their job is to relay information to you.<br>
<br>
Ignorance is okay, at times. We know that not everyone trolls these boards like a certain ranger (/me wonders who I am talking about) and some have actual lives. But! If you don't be quite and listen, you will miss some information that you need! Have a question? Ask. But, also pay attention, because that question may have been answered in the chat channel five times already.<br>
<br>
Zym is correct, your group leader will most likely have some foreknowledge of what is going on. (Zym was in my group. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) I reiterated everything that was said and answered any questions I could. It's okay to not know what spells to have up. Ask. It's okay to not know when you should cast. Ask. If the GL doesn't know, they will find out.<br>
<br>
So to recap<br>
1) Listen - Very Important Rule.<br>
2) Ask Questions of your group leader, chat channel, or Spammers<br>
3) Don't send RL tells, it only makes the long wait longer.<br>
4) Turn LFG on and Anon and Role off. Otherwise you wont get a group. <p><img src="http://www.talonswitch.com/qamcard.jpg"><br>
